data.title: An exciting educational family tour of the Everglades Ecosystem with caveats!
data.content: We took our two 6 & 7 year old grandchildren on the tour and alligator show on an overcast, slightly rainy Monday when the pool was not an option. The park is easy to find with GPS and close by Ft. Lauderdale. There's ample parking and the site is well run and organized. Adult admissions are $15 each, Children's tickets purchased on Groupon were $13.25 each,but buy them on the Holiday park website and they're only $11 per child. Our total cost for 2 adults and 2 children was $52! After purchasing tickets wait by the docks on benches under shaded sun ports for your number to be called. Have a friend take your family picture because the park guides take them and will be happy to sell you an 8 x 10" for $10 after you exit the boat ride.We declined them since we took our own. Really with everyone bringing cameras and cameraphones this is a lame, anarchronistic moneymaking stunt. We were at the front of the line and were able to sit in the front row. Since it was raining the visibility out the plexiglass windshield was limited there was ample viewing out the sides. The driver constantly turns the boat so port and starboard passengers get good views. There are many photo ops. Just set your camera vibration control "on."  Our guide, Rich, was very funny and a wealth of knowledge about the history and wildlife in the ecosystem. As an adult I found the tour educational and enjoyable. My grand kids loved it too. The older girl had already studied alligators in school so this field trip was a valuable field experience. The tour was one hour long. After about 40 minutes the similar views become tiresome. We did not see that much wildlife; two alligators, groups of vultures, an egret, and some grackles, starlings, and iridescent peahens that came to the boat to be fed popcorn.The driver guns the engines on three occasions and the boat flies on plane with the front off the water! The noise is deafening.  Bring ear plugs.This ride trumps one on a roller coaster. There was a two year old girl behind us who was so frightened she cried the entire ride. I would rate this attraction appropriate for ages 5 and up. At the end of the ride our driver Rich made his pitch for tips by announcing: "We work for tips so if you enjoyed my tour any tips would be greatly appreciated." I thought this was a venal act and resented him shaming guests into giving gratuities. Yes, he did earn it but I don't need to be prodded to fork over the dollars. Gratuities are earned and people will respond if they desire to do so. Broward County or whoever runs the park should be responsible for seeing that their are adequately reimbursed. I know FL is a "right to work state." Are these drivers not paid as stated? Shame on Broward County. We left the boat, declined the $10 photo, and lined up for the alligator show by the "Gator Boys." Be forewarned...stand in front or wait for the next show or you will not get a place where your children can see the show. We were at the end of the line. You don't want to be here if you bring young children. When the crowd was admitted all the adults ran to grab all the positions along the fence. There is a 4 ft. high wall in the pit and then protective fencing above that. No tiered seating exists as in Seaworld Miami. Our grandchildren has no place to stand and view the show so I had to hold my 6 year old grandaughter on my shoulders which was temporary. The "Gator Boys" need to be trained in audience control. A simple "Adults, please step back and permit the younger shorter children to stand in front so they can see the show." The adults there were selfish and no one volunteered to let the children move in front of them. There were over a dozen huge protected alligators inside that the kids could not see. We got frustrated and left early. Afterwards we ate the picnic lunch we brought. There are ample picnic tables under sunports for sitting and eating, as are outdoor clean bathrooms. Bring a picnic lunch, leave it in the car which you park below the decks, and eat an enjoyable meal. There are food and drinks available but you can save $$$$ bringing your own drinks and food. The park admissions are expensive enough without having to buy food for a family of six or more. Want to see more? Don't miss the Shark Valley trip. Many more alligators seen close up or from the observation tower. Take a bike tour or a tram ride tour.

data.title: Fun little diversion
data.content: The park was much smaller (and more crowded!) than I expected.  Overall, it was a mildly entertaining way to spend 1-2 hours.  You wouldn't want to stay there longer.  In a nutshell, you buy a ticket for an airboat ride through the Everglades.  You then wait for them to call your ticket number (we waited for 15-20 minutes).  You get on a boat with about 15-20 people.  Together, you spend an hour seeing alligators swimming alongside you, native birds, and learn about the local foliage.  Interesting stuff, and certainly worth an hour's ride.Then, and only after the boat ride, can you see the alligator show.  This wasn't really what I expected in that it's not much of a show.  You line up down a long area and stand to watch a guy get in a fenced off area with a dozen alligators.  He chooses one of them, hold the alligator's mouth open, then closed, then open, then closed, then puts his head against the teeth... all while cracking jokes and saying how dangerous this is (which I believe).  The entire "show" lasts about 10 minutes (maybe less).  I kept thinking it was the pre-show or something, until we were filed out when it was over.Overall, it's a little park, with a small gift shop, a place to line up for your airboat ride and a little (as in not long) alligator show.  However, it was an interesting experience for a change of pace from the beach.  If you have a day where you don't know what else to do, it's worth an hour or two of your time.

data.title: Lots of fun, good value.
data.content: I did a lot of research before picking which airboat ride to do while in the area and I'm glad we picked Everglades Holiday Park. First off, it was the closest park to our hotel in Weston, only about 20 minutes away. It was also one of the cheapest running about $25 for adults. They have an Internet coupon for $3 off as well as a military discount which was 50% off! They had some others like a senior discount, etc. The airboat ride was pretty interesting. It was in a large 30 person airboat so the tour wasn't very personal but the boat had a roof which was really nice to keep our 2 year old out of the sun. The ride was only an hour so there wasn't time to go very far but we did see 2 alligators, 1 small 2 footer and one mom about 8 feet and also got to see her nest of mud which was pretty cool. We also saw a lot of different birds. They had an alligator show after the tour by the gator boys who you may have seen on animal planet. It was interesting and you got to get up close to a bunch of big alligators and touch a little one if you wanted. They did charge for lots of little stuff like a group picture at the airboat ride and to hold the alligator or to sit on one. They also asked for tips and donations but they pretty much earned it. It wasn't the most incredible tour I've ever been on but I can't think of any reason not to give it a 5 of 5. It was close, inexpensive and met all my expectations.

data.content: We went on 3/1/2015 on advice of our son and daughter in law  who went late last year,  I was excited to take a ride on a  fast airboat and talked my wife into going,  we were first in line and on the boat sitting up front,  our captain. ..captain Mike. ..was funny and really pumped up everyone on our boat about the  BIG CADILLAC 500 ENGINES...the hold on to your hats speech etc . etc etc.  As we were ready for our 1st run down the  "SPEED" LANE he gunned it and off we went, picking up speed but it sure didn't seem so fast and something just sounded wrong,  soon we slowed down and captain Mike said something went wrong with an engine and he was going to try to fix it, after messing around with it for a while he said his boss was bringing out another boat, 20 minutes from breakdown his boss showed up with parts to fix the problem,  turns out 1 engine threw a belt so no power to the prop. Ok boats fixed, time for the speed lane with both engines working fine right  ?? Wrong, same engine threw the new belt so we continued on at snails pace, saw 2 gators,  lots of birds and countless other airboats from their place racing down the speed lanes at full power, Bottom line for us, we expected to have the ride we paid for,  a little speed and excitement mixed in with slow search for gators, we got half....we still enjoyed our visit and would recommend this place but it just wasn't our day on our first trip to Fort Lauderdale .

data.title: Definitely not for a Florida Native.  For tourists,  this place will live up to expectations
data.content: I guess the biggest disappointment is that I've been in Florida for 6 years.  I go fishing all the time.  The sights,  wildlife and food are all a part of everyday life.  I was hoping for something to WOW me,  learn something new.  It's definitely geared towards those from out of state.  Being a big fan of the show,  I was hoping to see my favorite guys doing their work.  I did not.  That's the bigges draw to that place! Again,  disappointing.  They do have some of the best,  covered airboats around for the tours however,  definitely making that a stand out feature from other tours.  The guides do know what they are talking about.  The gift shop and mini restaurant do offer good products at reasonable prices.  The frog legs are delicious,  especially with the buffalo ranch sauce.  I love my gator and my frog legs and these guys did not disappoint.  Overall,  if you're visiting from out of state,  it's a place to visit,  maybe catch a glimpse of the TV show stars.  If you have lived in Florida for any length of time,  it's a place to just stop by and go fishing or launch your boat at.  Personally,  if you want to get up close and personal with wildlife and have a blast while going fishing,  I'd highly recommend adding Lake Okeechobee to your itinerary and take an airboat tour with Big O Airboat Tours or a fishing guide trip with any of the captains out of Clewiston for some mega bass fishing.  Not taking away from Everglades Holiday Park,  because of you like that,  you'll love this as well.  Have fun,  be safe and don't leave home without sunscreen and mosquito spray!

data.content: When is a swamp not a swamp?  When it's a wildlife preserve with guided tours. We visited during Spring Break, but the wait for an airboat ride wasn't too bad. data.content: This is a great park to visit and well maintained. Amenities include bike trails, one of which is on a canal next to the Everglades, there are playgrounds for the kiddies, boat rentals, nature trail and tennis courts. The park also includes some pretty uncommon amenities also. There is a shooting range and there is also an rc airfield. I haven't visited the shooting range but the radio controlled airplane field is great, especially for the children. Here you will see many radio controlled airplanes flying and many rc enthusiasts.The park also includes a campground. The park allows for both rv and tent camping. There is also a primitive camping site. We tent camped, the site included water, electricity, and even Wi-Fi. The campground includes a bathhouse and dump station. The sites are pretty well spaced and we were lucky enough to have four of the sites next to us open. A tip, the most northern sites of the campground are the one's closest to the shooting range. Also, if you camp over the weekend be sure to stop by the Fox Observatory. Hopefully you have clear skies, the professional astronomers will let you view far off planets and galaxies.

data.title: Great "Old Florida" experience!
data.content: We had to stay overnight in Fort Lauderdale after a cruise, and needed something to do in the afternoon with three kids who were coming off their first cruise (and therefore used to something new and great everyday!)  We saw the ad for Everglades Holiday Park in the local South Florida guide which had a coupon for $3 off adults and $2 off children (who must be 11 and under)The place was packed when we pulled up, full of locals for the fishing and tourists for the taking.  The cost for our family of five was $75 (with coupons, tax, and oldest daughter was considered an adult) for both the one hour airboat tour and the alligator "wrestling" show.  Have just come off a cruise, this was one cheap shore excursion (think of it this way, it was $15 pp).  To add to the shore excursion feel of the place, they even took our photo before the tour and offered it for sale for $10 when we returned (we did buy it, it was great looking and $10 5x7 plus a keychain...i.e. we forgot the camera at the hotel!!)The tour was with an old-salt "I live in the Everglades" guide who was awesome.  We learned "a bunch of factual useless stuff" about the Everglades, enjoyed whipping through the Glades at high speeds and saw three adult alligators, one three year old and one baby less than a foot long.  In addition, we learned about and saw native birds, exotic species and iguanas (big four footers up in the trees!)  Our guide made sure everyone got to see the gators we came across.  Our older daughter, who is highy skeptical of everything, actually enjoyed the tour (red letter day).The alligator demostration afterwards was short, informative and pure old florida tourist trap at its finest.  We absolutely loved it, and tipped generously.This is not for everyone--but for family fun and a nostalgic trip back to the touristy Florida of the fities/sixties that I could share with my kids--well worth it!

data.content: The Anne Kolb Nature Center is beautifully maintained both inside and out. We enjoyed a relaxing day kayaking up and down the waterways. data.title: "See nature's wonder!"
data.content: Im really glad my family and I finally got to visit one of United Nations Education Scientific Cultural Organization (UNESCO) World Heritage Park! My family and I purchased an air-boat tour and it was fantastic. First of all, the tour guide was hilarious (Captain Don), he was very experienced and informative. Everyone on the boat enjoyed him! The boats were comfortable, lots of space to sit. The boats have roofs so you don't have to worry about getting sunburned or a little wet if it starts to drizzle! We got to see 4 alligators, and beautiful exotic birds that my kids got to feed! Also, before we stepped onto the air-boats they take a free family/group photo of you and you get to receive it after the boat ride. The alligator show was very exciting too. You learn more about alligators, very educational and thrilling if I must say. My family and I will definitely be back again and probably camp there next time!

data.title: Better Than South Beach
data.content: If there's a beach in South Florida you should visit its Fort Lauderdale Beach on Las Olas Boulevard. This beach is far better than over rated South Beach and with restaurants right across the street, who can go wrong. The water can be rough at times and with the intrusion of seaweed in the Caribbean and South Florida, this beach is not exempt.

data.title: Well worth it..
data.content: I dont know about anybody else's experience but when we went today.. my family had a blast. ok so we may be "Northerners" .. but we have never been on a Airboat before. Having read other reviews before we went.. we did bring water because it was Hot and brought some mosquito spray.. (which mosquitos werent bad at all). The Airboat ride was awesome. the captain was funny & extremely knowledgable.. ride was about and hour and we saw 3 Gators.. he also showed us some birds which flew over and the kids fed them by hand..  it was worth it. After, we saw the Gator Boys show which was around 10minutes long.. they informed us about the Gators & showed us some tricks. I dont know about anybody else, but I enjoyed the Gator show.. I mean how long should it be??  How many times you want to see somebody attempt to stick their head in the Gator's mouth before he gets caught?? My kids loved it and thats all that matters.. we tipped the Airboat Captain and the Gator Boys.. my thought is.. why not?? They deserved it.. yeah they said Gratuities are Appreciated & we felt they deserved it.. I certainly would prefer tipping them as opposed to a Bum or somebody holding up a fake sign on I-95 begging for money... I think it was 100% worth it and would go back again.. Bathroom was clean and the staff was friendly!!!! Definately bring Water if you go during summer months!!! Only bummer.. sell stuff that says GATOR BOYS on it.. tshirts, hats.. etc.. other than that .. was well worth it..

data.title: Great Airboat Captain and Tour
data.content: My family visited the Everglades Holiday Park last Saturday during a family reunion weekend. There were 13 of us and we all bought the Airboat tour with the Gator Boys Show. Our Airboat tour guide was Swamp Thing and he was great. He's 4th generation South Florida Gladesman and was very entertaining and knowledgeable. He spotted 4 alligators during the tour, we got within a few feet of one about 10 feet long and all of got great videos and photos of it. The tour lasted about 80 minutes and then we waited for the Gator Show. The Gator Show was just okay, the host was knowledgeable but it was not a "show."  It was basically a Q&A with the crowd and discussing how they rescue alligators.
